Yes. The user is **not reaching the API successfully because of proxy / authentication issues**.

What the logs show:

1. Direct call to:

`https://ubo-proxy-benelux.dev.echonet/ubo/api/ubo`

fails with:

`curl: (35) Recv failure: Connection was reset`

and:

`schannel: failed to receive handshake, SSL/TLS connection failed`

So the TLS connection to the API host is being reset.

2. Then curl tries using the corporate proxy:

`http://nwbccproxy.be.fortis.bank:8080`

but the proxy replies:

`HTTP/1.1 407 authenticationrequired`

This means the proxy requires authentication, and curl is not authenticated against it.

Main issue:

`407 Proxy Authentication Required`

So the user cannot connect because their request is going through the bank proxy, but proxy authentication is missing or not being passed correctly.

They can try:

```bash
curl --proxy http://USERNAME:PASSWORD@nwbccproxy.be.fortis.bank:8080 \
  --request POST \
  --url https://ubo-proxy-benelux.dev.echonet/ubo/api/ubo \
  --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data '{"kvkNumber":"81408269"}' \
  -vvv
```

Or, if they are on Windows/BNP environment, try NTLM:

```bash
curl --proxy http://nwbccproxy.be.fortis.bank:8080 \
  --proxy-ntlm \
  --proxy-user DOMAIN\USERNAME:PASSWORD \
  --url https://ubo-proxy-benelux.dev.echonet/ubo/api/ubo \
  --header "Content-Type: application/json" \
  --data '{"kvkNumber":"81408269"}' \
  -vvv
```

Also check this: the screenshot shows `Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, not JSON, so the header may not be passed correctly. Use double quotes around headers/data.
